%26quot%3Bokay%20financially%26quot%3B%20dropped%20from%2069%25%20in%202022%20to%2064%25%20in%202023.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%202023%20data%20point%20is%20a%20stark%20decline%20from%202021%20when%2075%25%20of%20parents%20said%20they%20felt%20comfortable%20financially.%20Data%20from%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20shows%20that%20parents%20haven't%20felt%20this%20financially%20insecure%20since%202015%2C%20when%20it%20recorded%2065%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EComparatively%2C%20the%20percentage%20of%20adults%20who%20don't%20have%20children%20under%2018%20and%20feel%20%26quot%3Bokay%20financially%26quot%3B%20hasn't%20dipped%20below%2070%25%20in%20the%20last%20eight%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20report%20doesn't%20give%20specific%20reasons%20for%20the%20growing%20financial%20concern%2C%20but%20the%20rising%20cost%20of%20childcare%20has%20been%20a%20national%20concern%20for%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20cost%20of%20childcare%20has%20skyrocketed%20in%20the%20United%20States%2C%20making%20it%20difficult%20for%20families%20to%20maneuver%20the%20current%20economy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BChildcare%20costs%20can%20be%20significant%20for%20parents%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20report%20says.%20%26quot%3BThe%20median%20monthly%20amount%20that%20parents%20using%20paid%20care%20paid%20for%20childcare%20was%20%24800.%20For%20those%20who%20paid%20for%2020%20or%20more%20hours%20of%20childcare%20each%20week%2C%20the%20median%20cost%20was%20%241%2C100.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBusiness%20Insider%20estimated%20that%20it%20could%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhow-much-kids-cost-raising-child-inflation-childcare-tax-exemptions-2024-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecost%20parents%20nearly%20%2426%2C000%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20year%20to%20care%20for%20one%20child%20in%202024%3Cstrong%3E%3Cs%3E%20%3C%2Fs%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%E2%80%94%20a%2041.5%25%20increase%20from%202016.%20A%202024%20Bank%20of%20America%20analysis%20also%20found%20that%20the%20United%20States%20h